11|Defining Your Core Values and Non-Negotiables|<p><strong>What the decision really is</strong></p><p> This is not about writing a list of virtues. It is the decisionoften unconsciousabout <strong>what you will trade for what</strong>, and where you will draw hard lines even when incentives push the other way. High-agency people eventually discover that life repeatedly offers profitable opportunities that quietly violate something important. Values are the rules you install <em>before</em> pressure arrives.</p><p><strong>Typical circumstances when this arises</strong></p><p> This decision usually surfaces indirectly:</p><ul><li>Early career compromises (just for now)</li><li>First major financial upside with ethical ambiguity</li><li>A relationship that conflicts with ambition or integrity</li><li>A leadership role where cutting corners is normalized</li></ul><p>Most people think theyll define values later, when theyre successful enough. In practice, success amplifies whatever values were <em>implicitly</em> chosen earlier. If they werent chosen deliberately, they were chosen by defaultoften by parents, culture, or fear.</p><p><strong>Forces acting on the decision</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Short-term incentives</strong>: money, approval, status</li><li><strong>Social gravity</strong>: peers normalize behavior quickly</li><li><strong>Narrative pressure</strong>: everyone does this, this is how it works</li><li><strong>Ambiguity</strong>: ethical lines are rarely clear-cut in the moment</li></ul><p>High-agency individuals are especially vulnerable here because they encounter more edge casesgray zones where rules are flexible and enforcement is weak.</p><p><strong>Common mistakes and traps</strong></p><ol><li><strong>Abstract values with no cost</strong></li><li> Integrity, freedom, or family first mean nothing unless they imply a concrete sacrifice.</li><li><strong>Borrowed values</strong></li><li> Adopting values that sound admirable but dont align with your temperament or goals.</li><li><strong>Situational ethics</strong></li><li> Adjusting principles retroactively to justify a beneficial outcome.</li><li><strong>Delayed definition</strong></li><li> Waiting until a crisis forces a rushed moral decision.</li></ol><p><strong>Second-order consequences</strong></p><ul><li>Values determine <strong>who trusts you</strong> and <strong>who avoids you</strong></li><li>They silently shape your <strong>risk profile</strong></li><li>They filter opportunities long before conscious choice</li><li>Over decades, they compound into reputationearned or lost</li></ul><p>People often underestimate how <em>predictable</em> their future becomes once values are clear. You stop debating every fork in the road.</p><p><strong>How people rationalize poor choices</strong></p><ul><li>This is temporary.</li><li>Ill fix it later.</li><li>I deserve this after everything Ive done.</li><li>Im playing a different game now.</li></ul><p>These rationalizations feel intelligent in the moment and obvious in hindsight.</p><p><strong>What matters in hindsight</strong></p><p> Almost no one regrets having <em>clear</em> values. Many regret discovering theirs only after violating them.</p>|3|1
12|Defining What Success Means for You|<p><strong>What the decision really is</strong></p><p> This is a <strong>constraint-setting decision</strong>. Success definitions dictate how you allocate time, energy, stress, and risk. Without a personal definition, you default to externally supplied metrics: income, titles, lifestyle optics, or comparison.</p><p>High-agency individuals often excel early and then feel disoriented laternot because they failed, but because they succeeded at goals they never consciously chose.</p><p><strong>Typical circumstances</strong></p><ul><li>After first major career or financial milestone</li><li>When external praise increases but internal satisfaction doesnt</li><li>When peers begin diverging radically in life choices</li><li>Mid-30s to mid-40s reassessment after years of momentum</li></ul><p>This decision often appears disguised as burnout, boredom, or is this it?</p><p><strong>Forces acting on the decision</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Status signaling</strong> (especially among high performers)</li><li><strong>Survivorship bias</strong> (copying visible winners)</li><li><strong>Delayed costs</strong> (health, relationships, meaning)</li><li><strong>Comparison traps</strong> amplified by social media</li></ul><p>The danger is not ambitionits <strong>unexamined ambition</strong>.</p><p><strong>Common mistakes</strong></p><ol><li><strong>Single-metric success</strong></li><li> Optimizing for money alone, or freedom alone, or impact alone.</li><li><strong>Inherited definitions</strong></li><li> Chasing success your parents or peers value, not you.</li><li><strong>Static definitions</strong></li><li> Refusing to update success criteria as circumstances change.</li><li><strong>Post-hoc justification</strong></li><li> Defining success as whatever your current path happens to produce.</li></ol><p><strong>Second-order consequences</strong></p><ul><li>Determines stress tolerance and burnout risk</li><li>Shapes partner compatibility</li><li>Dictates acceptable trade-offs (health, time, ethics)</li><li>Influences how you experience wins and losses emotionally</li></ul><p>Two people with identical lives but different success definitions can experience radically different satisfaction.</p><p><strong>Rationalizations</strong></p><ul><li>I can rebalance later.</li><li>This is the price of winning.</li><li>I dont want to limit myself.</li></ul><p>In reality, not defining success doesnt preserve freedomit hands control to circumstance.</p><p><strong>Hindsight insight</strong></p><p> Success without definition often feels hollow. Failure with a clear definition often feels meaningful.</p>|3|1

contenteditable="false"></span> Forming worldview solely in reaction to pain or injustice.</li></ol><p><strong>Second-order consequences</strong></p><ol><li data-list="bullet"><span class="ql-ui" contenteditable="false"></span>How you respond to failure</li><li data-list="bullet"><span class="ql-ui" contenteditable="false"></span>Whether you persist or disengage</li><li data-list="bullet"><span class="ql-ui" contenteditable="false"></span>How you judge others</li><li data-list="bullet"><span class="ql-ui" contenteditable="false"></span>Your tolerance for uncertainty
